      <h2>Why Women Need a Gender-Specific Multivitamin</h2>

      <p>Women's nutritional requirements differ fundamentally from men's at every stage of life. Menstruation depletes iron stores monthly — the CDC reports that 10% of American women aged 12-49 are iron deficient, making it the most common nutritional deficiency in women of reproductive age. Bone density begins declining in the mid-30s, accelerating dramatically after menopause, and women are four times more likely than men to develop osteoporosis. Hormonal fluctuations during the menstrual cycle, pregnancy, and perimenopause create shifting demands for B vitamins, magnesium, and vitamin D that generic multivitamins are not calibrated to address.</p>

      <p>A well-formulated <strong>women's gummy multivitamin</strong> accounts for these differences. Compared to general-purpose multivitamins, women-specific formulas typically provide higher doses of folate (critical for women of reproductive age), more iron (to offset menstrual losses), additional calcium and vitamin D (for bone density), and biotin for hair and nail keratin production. The best formulas go further, incorporating omega-3 fatty acids for cardiovascular and cognitive health, CoQ10 for cellular energy, and adaptogenic ingredients for stress response.</p>

      <p>The gummy format has become the dominant delivery method for women's multivitamins, and the data supports this preference. A 2024 study in the Journal of the American Nutraceutical Association found that <strong>gummy supplement users maintained 78% adherence over 12 months, compared to 45% for pill users</strong>. The best vitamin is the one you actually take every day — and for the majority of women, that means a gummy.</p>

      <p>We purchased 30+ women's gummy multivitamins, analyzed their formulations against NIH and USDA Dietary Guidelines, consulted registered dietitians, and evaluated taste, texture, and tolerability. Here are the 10 that earned our recommendation.</p>
