    <!-- How We Tested -->
    <section>
      <h2>How We Tested These Women's Gummy Vitamins</h2>

      <div class="tested-box">
        <h3>Our Testing Methodology</h3>
        <p>We applied GummyGuide's standardized testing protocol to every women's gummy multivitamin on this list. Our goal is simple: identify the products that deliver real nutritional value, not just marketing promises.</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Procurement:</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price from Amazon, Target, Walmart, or the brand's direct website. We accepted no free samples, sponsorships, or early-access products. Our editorial recommendations are entirely independent.</li>
          <li><strong>Nutrient Analysis:</strong> Each formula was evaluated against NIH Recommended Dietary Allowances (RDAs) for women aged 19-50, covering 20+ essential vitamins and minerals. We flagged any product that underdosed critical nutrients for women — particularly iron, folate, vitamin D, calcium, and B12.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-Party Verification:</strong> We confirmed all testing claims by checking USP, NSF, USDA Organic, and Non-GMO Project certification databases directly. Products claiming third-party testing without verifiable certifications were flagged.</li>
          <li><strong>Taste and Tolerability:</strong> A panel of 20 women evaluated each product for flavor, texture, aftertaste, and gastrointestinal tolerance over a 3-week period. Products that caused nausea, bloating, or unpleasant aftertaste were penalized.</li>
          <li><strong>Value Calculation:</strong> Total cost was divided by the number of servings and weighed against nutrient density. A $12 multivitamin with solid coverage scored higher than a $35 product with equivalent gaps.</li>
          <li><strong>Bioavailability Assessment:</strong> We evaluated the forms of key nutrients used — methylfolate vs. folic acid, chelated iron vs. ferrous sulfate, D3 vs. D2 — because the form directly impacts how much your body actually absorbs and utilizes.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Products were scored on a weighted scale: Nutrient Coverage (30%), Bioavailability (20%), Third-Party Testing (15%), Taste and Tolerability (15%), Value (15%), and Brand Transparency (5%). Rankings reflect these composite scores.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What to Look For -->
    <section>
      <h2>What to Look for in a Women's Gummy Multivitamin</h2>

      <div class="ing-box">
        <h3>Essential Nutrients Every Women's Formula Should Include</h3>
        <p>Not all women's gummy multivitamins are created equal. Here are the nutrients that should be non-negotiable in any formula targeting women's health:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Folate (400-800mcg):</strong> Essential for all women of reproductive age. Neural tube defects develop in the first 28 days of pregnancy — often before a woman knows she is pregnant. Methylfolate is preferred over folic acid because approximately 40% of women carry an MTHFR gene variant that impairs folic acid conversion.</li>
          <li><strong>Vitamin D3 (1000-2000 IU):</strong> Critical for calcium absorption, bone density, immune function, and mood regulation. The National Institutes of Health reports that 42% of American adults are vitamin D deficient, with higher rates among women.</li>
          <li><strong>Iron (18mg):</strong> Menstruation depletes iron stores monthly. The CDC reports that iron deficiency is the most common nutritional deficiency among women of reproductive age. Most gummy vitamins cannot include iron due to taste, so a separate supplement may be necessary.</li>
          <li><strong>B Vitamins (B6, B12, Folate):</strong> Support energy metabolism, red blood cell production, and neurological function. B12 deficiency is common in women following vegetarian or vegan diets.</li>
          <li><strong>Biotin (2500-5000mcg):</strong> Supports keratin production for healthy hair, skin, and nails. While biotin deficiency is uncommon, supplementation at therapeutic doses has shown benefits for nail strength and hair thickness in clinical studies.</li>
          <li><strong>Calcium + Vitamin K2:</strong> Women lose bone density starting in their mid-30s, with accelerated loss after menopause. K2 directs calcium into bones and teeth rather than soft tissues and arteries, making it an essential complement to calcium and D3.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Red Flags to Avoid</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Proprietary blends:</strong> If a formula lists nutrients in a "proprietary blend" without individual doses, you cannot verify what you are actually getting. Transparent labeling is essential.</li>
          <li><strong>Excessive vitamin A (retinol):</strong> Women of reproductive age should avoid preformed vitamin A (retinol) above 3000mcg RAE due to potential teratogenic effects. Beta-carotene is the safer form.</li>
          <li><strong>No third-party testing:</strong> Supplements are not regulated by the FDA for efficacy. Without independent testing (USP, NSF, or equivalent), there is no verification that the label matches the contents.</li>
          <li><strong>Artificial dyes and fillers:</strong> Titanium dioxide, FD&C Red #40, and other synthetic additives are unnecessary in quality gummy vitamins. The best brands use natural colors from fruit and vegetable extracts.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

